    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen your buffer has a concealed line, and you left click on the line beneath the concealed line, the cursor doesn't jump to the line you click on; it reveals the concealed line and jumps there. This means it is impossible to use the mouse to put your cursor on a line beneath a concealed line.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```lua\nvim.opt.conceallevel = 3\nvim.opt.number = true\n\n--[[this comment will be concealed]]\nlocal line_to_conceal = 3\n-- click here ^ with the mouse\n\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd('BufReadPost', {\n  callback = function()\n    local ns = vim.api.nvim_create_namespace(\"my_namespace\")\n    local bufnr = vim.api.nvim_get_current_buf()\n    vim.api.nvim_buf_set_extmark(bufnr, ns, line_to_conceal, 0, {conceal_lines = ''})\n  end\n})\n```\n\n```sh\nnvim --clean -u repro.lua repro.lua\n```\n\nYour buffer will have this in it: [note that line 4 is concealed]\n```\n 3\n 5 local line_to_conceal = 3\n 6 -- click here ^ with the mouse\n```\nLeft click on the letter `c` in \"line_to_conceal\".\nNote that your cursor is NOT placed on the letter you clicked.\nNote that your cursor is placed on the letter `n` in \"this comment will be concealed\" in line 4.\nNote that the concealed line was revealed.\n\nLeft click again on the letter `c` in \"line_to_conceal\".\nNote that your cursor is again NOT placed on the letter you clicked.\nNote that the cursor is on the `^` character in line 6.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nWhen I click a line, my cursor should be placed on the specfic character that I click.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.11.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux 2025-04-13\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nKonsole\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nsudo pacman -S neovim",
